es}}\n| birth_place   = [[Bridgend]], [[Glamorgan]]\n| Sport country = {{WAL}}\n| Professional = 2002/2003, 2016\u20132018\n| High ranking = 95 <small>(June 2017)\n| Prize money  = [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]110,600\n| High break   = '''131''': <br> <small>2017 Gibraltar Open</small>\n| Century break = 5\n| Best finish  = ''Last 64'' <small>([[2017 Snooker Shoot-Out|2017 Shoot-Out]], [[2017 Gibraltar Open]])</small>\n| Ranking wins = \n| Other wins   = \n| World champ  = \n}}\n\n'''David''' \"'''Dai'''\" '''John''' (born 24 November 1984 in [[Bridgend]], [[Glamorgan]]) is a [[Welsh people|Welsh]] former professional [[snooker]] player.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early years===\nJohn drew attention in 2000 by reaching the quarter-finals at the [[EBSA European Under-21 Snooker Championships|European Under-19 Championship]]. His first major success occurred in 2002 when he won the [[EBSA European Snooker Championships|EBSA European Championship]] after defeating [[David McLellan (snooker player)|David McLellan]] 7\u20132, he continued this success at amateur level for the remainder of the year and reached the final of the [[IBSF World Under-21 Snooker Championship]] lost but 9\u201311 against [[China|China's]] [[Ding Junhui]].\n\nFor the [[Snooker season 2002/2003|2002/03 snooker season]] John joined the [[World Snooker Tour|main tour]]. In the first world ranking tournament of the season, the [[2002 LG Cup (snooker)|2002 LG Cup]], John secured a 5\u20133 win against [[Andrew Higginson]] before being eliminated in the following round by [[Martin Dziewialtowski]]. After this John struggled for much of the season with his best performance of the season came in the [[2003 Welsh Open (snooker)|2003 Welsh Open]] where John reached the [[2003 Welsh Open (snooker)#Qualifying|third qualifying round]] before losing 4\u20135 to future [[World Snooker Championship|World Champion]] [[Mark Selby]] in a final frame decider. John finished the season [[Snooker world rankings|ranked 111th]] .\n\nIn June 2003, John defeated fellow [[Welsh people|countryman]] [[Andrew Pagett]] 7\u20133 to retain the [[EBSA European Snooker Championships|EBSA European Championship]], becoming the first person to do so.<ref>{{cite web|title=2003 EBSA European Championships \u2013 Knock out draws|url=http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/EBSA/EURO2003euromensknockout.htm|publisher=Global Snooker Centre|accessdate=11 October 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090105160940/http://www.globalsnookercentre.co.uk/files/EBSA/EURO2003euromensknockout.htm|archivedate=5 January 2009}}</ref> As of 2016, John, [[Robin Hull]]  and [[Malta|Maltese]] player [[Alex Borg]] are the only players to have won the [[EBSA European Snooker Championships|EBSA European Championship]] twice.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ebsa.tv/index.php/k2/item/769-david-john-targeting-a-triple-crown | title=David John Targeting a Triple Crown | publisher=European Billiards & Snooker Association | accessdate=11 October 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011223851/http://www.ebsa.tv/index.php/k2/item/769-david-john-targeting-a-triple-crown | archive-date=11 October 2016 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Amateur years===\n{{quote box|quote= \u201cI should\u2019ve knuckled down for three or four years. I thought I could do both, get up at 5, get back at 2, but you can\u2019t do both. That\u2019s when my snooker started going downhill. I know the ability is still there, it\u2019s just the practice.\u201d |source= \u2014 David John<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9hJ-DkA9Zk4 | title=David John Victorious on Return to Snooker | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=11 October 2016}}</ref> |width=25%|align=right|style=padding:8px;}}\nHaving dropped off of the tour at the end of the [[Snooker season 2002/2003|2002/03 snooker season]] John spent the next 13 years playing as an amateur. During this time he twice won the [[Welsh Amateur Championship (snooker)|Welsh Amateur Championship]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.welshsnooker.com/news/504/welsh-championship-2016---result | title=Welsh Championship 2016 - Result | publisher=Welsh Snooker | accessdate=11 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, John entered [[2015 Australian Goldfields Open|Australian Goldfields Open]], defeating [[Snooker world rankings|world number 44]] [[Alfie Burden]] in the [[2015 Australian Goldfields Open#Qualifying stages|first qualifying round]] 5\u20131. Although he was ultimately defeated by [[Peter Lines]] by the same score in the following round, this performance encouraged John that he could still make a full-time return to the game at a professional level.\n\n===Return to professional status===\nAfter a 13-year absence John earned a place on the [[World Snooker Tour|main tour]] by coming through [[Q-School]] in 2016. He beat [[Zak Surety]] 4\u20131 in the final round of [[Q-School 2016/17 \u2013 Event 2|second event]] to secure a two-year tour card.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/q-school-event-2-qualifiers/ | title=Q School Event 2 Qualifiers | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=11 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018 he was suspended from the tour for suspected match fixing, although he had not accrued enough ranking points to stay on the main tour in any case.<ref>http://www.worldsnooker.com/wpbsa-statement-david-john/</ref>\n\n==Performance and rankings timeline==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"font-size:85%;\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! '''Tournament''' \n! [[Snooker season 2001/2002|2001/<br/>02]]\n! [[Snooker season 2002/2003|2002/<br/>03]]\n! [[Snooker season 2003/2004|2003/<br/>04]]\n! [[Snooker season 2004/2005|2004/<br/>05]]\n! [[Snooker season 2015/2016|2015/<br/>16]]\n! [[Snooker season 2016/2017|2016/<br/>17]]\n! [[Snooker season 2017/2018|2017/<br/>18]]\n|-\n| [[Snooker world rankings|Ranking]]<r